{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17637527","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17637527"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T18:43:36+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T18:43:36+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17665"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"17665","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/17665"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.08,0.25,0.04,0.38,0.25]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10379"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"71948"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"10379","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/10379"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17665"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"57418"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4933"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"8120"},{"type":"tags","id":"10006"},{"type":"tags","id":"10007"},{"type":"tags","id":"10520"},{"type":"tags","id":"10538"},{"type":"tags","id":"10544"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"24267"},{"type":"contributions","id":"24302"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"71948","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/71948"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EThe collecting duct of the nephron contains specialised cells that are responsible for acid-base regulation through proton secretion.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the mechanism of proton secretion by type A intercalated cells in the collecting duct?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Basolateral proton channel and apical chloride-bicarbonate exchanger","Apical potassium-hydrogen exchanger","Apical sodium-hydrogen exchanger","Basolateral H+-ATPase pump and apical sodium-bicarbonate cotransporter","Apical H+-ATPase pump and basolateral chloride-bicarbonate exchanger"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EType A intercalated cells use an \u003Cstrong\u003Eapical H+-ATPase pump and basolateral chloride-bicarbonate exchanger\u003C/strong\u003E to secrete protons into the tubular lumen. Inside the cell, carbonic anhydrase catalyses the formation of H+ and HCO3- from CO2 and H2O. The H+ is secreted via the apical H+-ATPase pump while HCO3- exits the cell through the basolateral exchanger.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect mechanisms can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBasolateral proton channel and apical chloride-bicarbonate exchanger\u003C/strong\u003E - This arrangement would transport protons in the wrong direction, moving them into the blood rather than the tubular lumen.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EApical potassium-hydrogen exchanger\u003C/strong\u003E - This transporter is not present in type A intercalated cells and would be an inefficient mechanism for proton secretion.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EApical sodium-hydrogen exchanger\u003C/strong\u003E - While this transporter is important in the proximal tubule, it is not the mechanism used by type A intercalated cells in the collecting duct.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBasolateral H+-ATPase pump and apical sodium-bicarbonate cotransporter\u003C/strong\u003E - This arrangement would result in proton accumulation within the cell rather than secretion into the lumen.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThis mechanism allows type A intercalated cells to secrete protons into the tubular lumen, contributing to urinary acidification and maintenance of acid-base balance.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Type A intercalated cells in the collecting duct secrete protons via an apical H+-ATPase pump and basolateral chloride-bicarbonate exchanger.","Proton secretion in the collecting duct is important for final urinary acidification and maintaining acid-base balance.","Carbonic anhydrase catalyses the formation of H+ and HCO3- from CO2 and H2O within type A intercalated cells."],"references":["Hall JE, Hall ME. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th ed. Philadelphia, PA: Elsevier; 2020.","Tortora, G. J., Mellifont, R., Derrickson, B., Burkett, B., Peoples, G., D, D. Principles of Anatomy and Physiology, Asia-Pacific Edition,  2nd Edition. John Wiley \u0026 Sons Australia; 2019."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"57418"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17665"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"57418","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/57418"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-20T20:27:02+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-20T20:28:17+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10379"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"71948"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"creat